attacks, or actively sought to cull the abundant giant population, they found that hill giants often carried a substantial amount of money and items (Likely claimed from previous victims.) that would fetch a good price to vendors.<br><br>  &quot;Hill giants don't typically wander in this part of the mountains.  There are drakes though.  Wait a minute ... do I look like your servant or something?&quot;  Millikin paused in her discourse of the habitat choices of the various creatures that inhabited Rathe Mountains when the realization hit her that she was being ordered around.<br><br>  &quot;Yes.&quot;  Valdayana replied.<br><br>  &quot;Then I want a regular salary if you're going to go around telling people I'm your servant.&quot;  Millikin glanced over at Saldaria who remained unmoving.<br><br>  &quot;You do.  I rune you when you're about to die and then you whine about it.&quot;<br><br>  &quot;That is not a regular salary and I am in no danger of dying to a hill giant here.&quot;  Millikin responded.<br><br>  &quot;I'm not the one saying you're my servant, you are.&quot;  Valdayana replied.<br><br>  &quot;What??&quot;  Millikin stared in surprise.  <br><br>  &quot;I'll even directly quote you.  ' I look like your servant.' &quot;<br><br>  &quot;That is NOT a direct quote.  I said  ' Wait a minute ... do I look like your servant or something.' &quot;  Millikin was taken aback that what she said would so deliberately and blatantly twisted in such an obvious manner.<br><br>  &quot;Go out and kill some hill giants anyway.&quot;  Valdayana waved dissuasively at the ranger.<br><br>  &quot;I told you, they don't wander around here.  They live in a valley not too far from here.&quot;<br><br>  &quot;You have two legs.  Walk.&quot;  Valdayana countered curtly.<br><br>     Millikin grumbled as she took stock of the arrows in her quiver and strung her bow to use.  After a few minutes, she turned to leave, intending to do exactly as demanded, lure a hill giant to this area and slay it, when Valdayana called out.<br><br>  &quot;Good.  If you hadn't left soon, I'd have had to curse you.&quot;  <br><br>Millikin stopped dead in her tracks.  There were many things she would tolerate (to a point) from the arrogant enchanter, including insults and being peremptorily ordered around like a lackey.  Direct threats were another matter altogether.<br><br>  &quot;That's it.&quot;  The ranger turned around and walked back, unstringing her bow in the process.<br><br>  &quot;What's it?&quot;  Valdayana inquired.  <br><br>  &quot;Hunt your own hill giants.&quot;  Millikin sat down on the ground, intent on not moving until Saldaria returned to full consciousness.<br><br>  &quot;Didn't you hear me threaten to curse you, ranger?&quot; <br><br>  &quot;You know, your voodoo doll is still out there missing somewhere.  But I dare you to.&quot;  Millikin sniffed derisively.  <br><br>  &quot;Are you sure about that?&quot;  Valdayana poked her in the shoulder.  <br><br>  &quot;How about this...  I double dare you.&quot;  She glared at the dark elf.  <br><br>  &quot;Remember, you asked for this.&quot;  <br><br>     A faint inflection of amusement could be detected in the enchanter's intonation as she traced an arcane pattern in midair in cadence with the incantation.  Eldritch energy flickered around the ranger's body, akin to witchlight.  Valdayana's mage sight permitted her to observe that the ranger momentarily transform into a red implike creature before the aura dissipated with the illusion.  For her own part, Millikin felt a strange burning sensation course through her body that quickly subsided.  In the distance, Millikin heard the yipping bark of a coyote almost like a mocking laugh.<br><br>  &quot;Hm.  Your appearance improved momentarily.  The spell may have backfired.&quot;  Valdayana looked appraisingly at the ranger.  Millikin looked down at herself but didn't see anything out of the ordinary and shrugged.  Saldaria came out of her meditative trance and did not give any indication that she was aware that the two of them had been quarreling.  <br>  <br>  &quot;Shall we set about to our hunt?&quot;  <br><br>     Soon the three of them headed for the temple dedicated to Cazic Thule, meeting up with Draugrim, Senwen, and Ashwith to hunt the raptors and lizard guards that prowled the area.  Employing magic to conceal herself with her surroundings, Millikin wandered the grounds to bait would-be predators into an ambush.  She noticed that her camouflage did not ever dissipate until she took action to break it.  <br><br>Later...<br><br>Millikin willed herself to transform into a wolf and swiftly ran through the Innothule swamp towards the borders of the Ro Desert.  The ranger mentally willed herself to transform to her natural form.  Nothing happened.  Startled, she made for the southern desert and still the transformation had not dissipated.  <br><br>  &quot;What is this?&quot;  Millikin recited a cantra to attempt to dispel the wolf form, to no avail.  Running through the desert with a fur coat was not an appealing prospect to the ranger but it looked like she had little choice.  She made her way to the Commonlands and still the wolf guise had not broken.  Once more she heard a coyote yipping and the blood in her veins froze for a moment.  <br><br>  &quot;Wonderful.  What exactly is this curse?&quot;  Millikin muttered to herself.  Eventually the magical energies that permitted the transformation were spent and the ranger reverted to her natural form.  &quot;I'll find out soon enough.&quot;<br><br>----------<br><br>Saldaria Snowspirit is the sole property of her creator and used only for role playing purposes with prior consent.  Do not duplicate.<br><br>Valdayana D`Varr is the sole property of her creator and used only for role playing purposes with prior consent.  Do not duplicate.<br><br>Millikin Erreene is the sole property of her creator for role