hy have you spent the past few weeks pestering me about the orb you found a while ago and wheedling under rocks and ash through the mountains of Skyfire for the others more recently?&quot;  Sontalak craned his neck to face the ranger, bringing himself eye level to her, his look of consternation caused the ranger to freeze in place.<br><br>  &quot;It's for another.&quot;  Millikin stated uneasily when the dragon fear dissipated and she could think coherently enough to reply.  &quot;She's spent time going through books and scrolls in the Skyshrine and knows much of the Ring of Scale also.&quot;   Sontalak snorted at the mention of the Ring of Scale, an outcast sect of the Claws of Veeshan.  <br><br>  &quot;I thought she might like something akin to this.&quot;  Millikin paused.<br><br>  &quot;Then perhaps your friend should do the work to acquire it.&quot;  Sontalak rumbled once again.  The mental image brought a grin to Millikin's face though it quickly vanished.<br><br>  &quot;I doubt she would lower herself to foraging, even if she could.&quot;<br><br>  &quot;Then why should she reap the benefits of your efforts, Ranger?&quot;<br><br>     Millikin paused to consider that question.  Indeed why was she even wasting her time?  Chances are the gift would be spurned outright.  Or worse, viewed as a bribe.  She quickly pushed aside that line of thought by deciding she would simply steel herself for the likely insults and deal with them when the time came.<br><br>  &quot;I suppose it is a means of requiting how I benefited from her efforts.&quot;   Millikin replied after a thoughtful pause.<br><br>  &quot;I see.&quot;  Sontalak replied.<br><br>  &quot;I'm not exactly adept with expressing my feelings.&quot;   The ranger explained.<br><br>  &quot;Actions speak for themselves, Ranger.&quot;  Sontalak remarked as he looked out into the wasteland ahead of them.  &quot;Are you going to continue with stories of your exploits with your shaman friend on the moon or do I wait until next time?&quot;  Another time she would recount to the aged dragon of her most recent sojourn into the Sshraeshza temple but for now, Millikin beamed as she began to recount to the dragon one of her and Saldaria's earlier forays into the Grey battling the Shissar and golems just outside the temple.<br><br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A> at: 4/28/02 11:55:38 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Arrowbringer </span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(4/27/02 9:53:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> An Introspection by Millikin Erreene<br><br><br>     Millikin tended to take into consideration any personality criticisms made about her, even if she did not acknowledge them initially.  After some objective consideration of her behavior (if one taking into consideration their own traits can really be considered objective) and inquiries from those she did openly respect, the general consensus was that her somewhat somber outlook could be construed as such by those not familiar with the ranger's true nature.<br><br>     Why did she care what the luhtmauyar thought of her?  Thinking rationally, the ranger knew perfectly well that Valdayana D`Varr held no regard for anyone but herself so why should her opinion of anyone (which is guaranteed to be low) matter.  Millikin herself wasn't sure if she held some small hope that the enchanter was not irredeemably evil.  She remembered Ashwith's warning that she could just as likely help someone out for the sheer feeling of power over them and not because she held a modicum of regard for them.  Though the warning made sense, the concept was foreign to Millikin.  Whenever she traveled or explored with others, she felt a sense of responsibility for their safety and took what means she could to ensure that they did survive.  How anyone could not share that sense of obligation was inconceivable to the ranger.  Was that not the entire purpose of working together?<br><br>     Maybe Millikin respected the enchanter beyond the comprehension that she was extremely skilled in her field in spite of the enchanter's disparaging comments about her race, competence as a ranger, or personality.  Though how or why she had no clue.  Millikin hid the fact that sometimes Valdayana's comments bothered her by simply ignoring them or replying with a half-felt rejoinder of her own.  They technically shouldn't bother her because they were either said to simply provoke her or validly point out a fault.  And maybe the latter fact was what Millikin respected about her.  She didn't know for sure.<br><br>     Millikin stared down at the crystalline disc lying on the table.  It took quite a bit of effort on her part to obtain the crystals to make it, and convince the dragon known as Sontalak to do so as well.  The ranger was not sure how she would react to the insulting rebuff that was likely to result from her offering it to the enchanter and the thought of simply sending it by courier was very appealing.  At least she wouldn't see the rejection firsthand.  The thought of the gift becoming impersonal though made her ultimately dismiss the idea of having it delivered.  Millikin decided to offer it firsthand and simply brace herself for the worst as she picked up the disc and slid it into her pocket as she headed out of her flat. <p>M. E.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Arrowbringer </span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(6/15/02 8:40:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> <br><br>Kaladim Port Authority<br><br>The enchanter casually strolled along the decks of the Sky Hawk, a two masted schooner heading towards Freeport.  Desiring to keep her whereabouts and current activities obscured, she opted to travel under the guise of a half elven spice merchant named Raven Yadan.  The disguise not only prevented her from being beleaguered or attacked by the elves and dwarves who live on the continent, but it also served to mislead any potential rivals or enemies from ascertaining the reasons for her presence.  Forever pursuing knowledge, no matter how recondite or obscure, the enchanter's business in Faedwyr was recently concluded with the acquisition of a journal of some long forgotten thaumathurgy practices.<br><br>As the Sky Hawk went underway, the enchanter noticed a wood elf standing near the ship's railing, readying a corded arrow into the short bow she held as she looked down at the waters.  <br><br>  'Trust a wood elf to find a way to complicate something as simple-minded as fishing.'  The half elf watched as she fired the arrow into the water.  As it streaked downward, the cord unfurled to reveal it was tied to the railing and soon the ranger started to pull the cord up and reveal her catch.  A codfish was impaled upon the arrow.<br><br>  &quot;You know, fishing is infinitely easier if you use a fishing pole and bait.&quot;  The half elf remarked as the ranger extracted her arrow and tossed her catch into a nearby basket.<br><br>  &quot;Yes, but I don't have either with me right now.  And this is an alternative.&quot;  The wood elf turned to the speaker and instantly the incognito enchanter recognized her.<br><br>  &quot;Ranger.&quot;  The half elf spoke half question, half statement.  The Feir` Dal nodded in affirmation and turned to get a better look at the individual.  The silver haired half elf was nearly six feet tall, steel grey eyes were hidden behind a pair of gold wire-rimmed spectacles.  And despite the fact that she was dressed in a silk wayfarer's chemise and loose fitting trousers, her mannerisms seemed to indicate to the ranger that the half elf was less at home aboard a ship than a mansion in some large city.<br><br>  &quot;Millikin Erreene.&quot;  The ranger set aside her bow and extended her hand in greeting.  For her own part, the half elf adjusted the spectacles she was wearing and glanced at the offered hand with a measured pause before taking the hand in greeting -- just long enough to be polite.<br><br>  &quot;Raven Yadan.&quot;  She responded, smiling faintly to the ranger, wiping her hand on a handkerchief she had removed from a pocket.  <br><br>  &quot;A pleasure.&quot;  Millikin turned to pick up her bow, hiding a faint smile at the display of snobbery.  &quot;Did you lose your book or something?&quot;  She readied another arrow.<br><br>  &quot;Excuse me?&quot;  Raven asked in a quizzical tone.  'How could she know about the journal?'  Instantly she studied Millikin in mild suspicion, masked as curiosity.<br><br>  &quot;The reading spectacles.&quot;   The ranger indicated with a slight gesture.  Something caught Raven's attention as Millikin turned back to the water.  The medicine pouch worn around the ranger's neck possessed an eldritch power that called to the enchanter.  This was not one of the myriad druidic talismans rangers and others of her ilk typically carried.<br><br>  &quot;The spectacles.  No.&quot;  Raven responded.  &quot;They simply help me to see better.  What is that you're wearing around your neck?  I've never seen that before.&quot;<br><br>  &quot;It's a medicine pouch.  It's used to hold spell components and similar objects.&quot;  Millikin replied, studying the water.<br><br>  &quot;Is that what yours possesses?&quot;  Raven's question seemed innocuous enough, but something about it gave Millikin pause.  'Why would it suddenly be of interest to someone who barely deigned to shake hands earlier?'<br><br>  &quot;No.  It carries an object I intend to give to someone else.&quot;  <br><br>  &quot;What sort of object?&quot;  <br><br>  &quot;Something I obtained a while ago.&quot;  Millikin fired another arrow, this time intentionally missing her target.  No other information was forthcoming.<br><br>  &quot;Better luck next time, I suppose.&quot;  Raven remarked, smiling faintly to her once again.<br><br>  &quot;Perhaps.&quot;  Millikin retrieved the arrow then tucked the pouch underneath her tunic before resuming her bow fishing.<br><br>  &quot;Good day to you then, Millikin Erreene.&quot;  Raven turned to leave, knowing she may have better luck with the ranger at a later time.<br><br>  &quot;Good afternoon, Ms. Yadan.&quot;  Millikin replied, watching the half elf depart from the corner of her eye.  'Why did she have the feeling she knew her from somewhere?'<br><br>M. E. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/uautumncrescendo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Autumn Crescendo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Auty the Primadonna</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(6/17/02 6:24:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> Felwith - Southern District<br><br>Shiobahn Fyrestrike (formerly Goldbrooke) sat quietly upon a small blanket by the lakeside in her home town.  Above her loomed the guilds of the magical arts, her own designation included amongst them, and every so often she could hear the workings of different defensive spells coming from above.  Her momentary solitude was dedicated to toying with a pouch of runes, identifying each of the marks upon them to further her research for greater spells.  Quasqueton had promised her even greater runes when he returned back from his quest, but the days seemed to grow longer and longer in his absence.  It was in this moment of study and reflection that she distinctly heard the soft footfalls of the sure-footed ranger approaching her.<br><br>A smile crept across the delicately defined high Elven face as she let the initial shock of the visit wear away, and Shio rose to her feet.  She stood taller than the ranger, though her frame more willowy, and her hair was quite obviously flame kissed by her deity of the arts, Solusek Ro, whom she called upon for the power of her spells.  She reached out her hands to the ranger as she spoke softly in the language of the elves "Creoso eska, tinu en'Tunare.  It is good to see you home cousin."  Millikin gripped her hands in return though her present mood was unreadable, as often it was, by her kin.  "Diol'lle, Shiobahn.  It is good to return once again."<br><br>Shiobahn studied her a moment, certain there was a tale to be told, but not knowing when the ranger would tell it, if she decided to speak of it at all.  "We shall catch up over a glass of Elven wine.  The day is still early and the tavern is open across town.  Just allow me to pack my things."  Shio did not offer much room for argument, though then she rarely did.  She quickly bent down to retrieve her runes, pouring them back into a small pouch that hung from her belt.  She carried a small myriad of trinkets this way, including a finely crafted golden bowl bearing a few small dings in the bottom which hinted at the fact she was not afraid to swing it at something if one of her spells was going awry, no matter how futile the attempt was.  Tucking her blanket into a backpack she then set off on foot along side her cousin to the tavern.<br><br>........................<br>Felwith - Northern District<br><br>A glass of Elven wine and a treat of a small fruit tart later the two sat together in an out of the way corner of the bar.  It was an enjoyable time filled with tales of adventure, many of Millikin's taking place in the frozen lands of Velious which intrigued Shio and much of Shio's having taken place another great distance away, in the newly explored moon of Luclin.  It was Millikin's comments of the wastelands in the far west reaches of the frozen continent that perked Shio's attention.  "Cousin, why have you come home from such great adventures?  And have you heard word of a Quasqueton?  He has been in those far reaching lands for some time up to now under quest of the Coldain.  I know he is allied to the dragon beasts that survive out there, but he has not sent word recently and I worry.  The last I knew he had enlisted the aid of the Troubadour Autumnwyld, but it is still a harsh land for wizard and bard alone."<br><br>She quickly saw the look of recognition in Millikin's eyes as she uttered the names, and a look of hope appeared upon her face.  She felt the matter bore further explanation and she quickly added in "Quas and I were bound together just this spring in a quiet ceremony under Ro's watchful eye.  It is a difficult balance some days, love and magic.  We did not make a spectacle of our union, I am sorry to have not informed you but it is nearly impossible to track the tracker." <br><br>...............................<br><br>Creoso eska, tinu en'Tunare  - Welcome home daughter of Tunare<br>Diol'lle, Shiobahn - Thank you, Shiobahn<br><br>Shiobahn Fyrestrike is the sole property of her creator and used only for role playing purposes. Do not duplicate.<br><br>Quasqueton Fyrestrike is the sol